<Document>
<name>Olympic Peninsula — US-101 Loop</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Olympic Peninsula — US-101 Loop</h2><p><i>Washington, USA · US-101, Port Angeles to Aberdeen via Forks and Lake Quinault</i></p><p><b>Three ecosystems in a day: glacier-cut peaks, temperate rainforest, wave-pounded coast.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>218 km (135 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>6–7 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–October; passable in winter but very wet</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Deer and elk on road, fog, RV traffic, sudden weather changes</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>375</td></tr></table><hr><p>Olympic National Park is three parks in one — glaciated peaks, the wettest temperate rainforest in North America, and a wild Pacific coast — and US-101 lets you sample all three. Hoh Rainforest averages 3,650 mm of rain a year; Hurricane Ridge above Port Angeles is alpine and snowy. The road never enters the actual interior of the park (no road does), but loops the perimeter through Forks (the Twilight town) and Quinault. Roosevelt elk are common; mountain lions live here but you'll likely never see one.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Hurricane Ridge (spur from Port Angeles)</b> — 30 km mountain road climbs to 1,597 m subalpine meadows with views to Vancouver Island. Often elk grazing in afternoon.</li><li><b>Lake Crescent</b> — 20 km glacial lake, 190 m deep. Marymere Falls trail (3 km round-trip) ends at a 27 m waterfall fern-grotto.</li><li><b>Hoh Rainforest (spur)</b> — The 'Hall of Mosses' loop — 1.3 km through Sitka spruce and bigleaf maple draped in club moss. Annual rainfall: 3.5–4.3 m.</li><li><b>Ruby Beach</b> — Sea stacks, driftwood logs the size of buses, tide pools at low tide. Photograph at sunset; check tide tables.</li><li><b>Kalaloch — Tree of Life</b> — Sitka spruce growing over a wash-out void with its roots forming an arch — the soil beneath is gone, the tree somehow remains.</li><li><b>Lake Quinault Lodge</b> — 1926 timber lodge facing the lake. Largest Sitka spruce in the world (58 m tall, 5.8 m diameter) is on the south shore.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
